{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d33ed28-d8aa-4525-a755-82df3532ef67","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n---\n\n### If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed in the container\n\nUse **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar or collect a dump instead:\n\n```powershell\n# Collect a dump (analyze offline)\ndotnet-dump collect -p <PID>\n```\n\n### Copying the file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n> **Tip:** For Windows containers specifically, if the EventPipe-based `dotnet-trace` isn't giving you what you need, you can also use **PerfView** or **ETW traces** from the host (since you have admin access) by targeting the container's process, which is visible in the host's process list. Run from the host:\n> ```powershell\n> PerfView.exe /acceptEULA collect -Duration:30 -ProcessID:<PID>\n> ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5567a826-b782-4a59-a94d-ad26f258dc8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":454,"requestId":"CB18:347368:1D2E25C:204BE12:6A0524EC"},"id":"58928176-e2a9-4a97-8d83-eeb3e444c1a4","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:27:19.386Z","parentId":"b9bd9ae6-03c0-4398-951c-32fc1094d84a"}
